l, Catie -- t14. Quakers, Puritans, and the Problem of Godly Loyalty in the Early Restoration / rWeimer, Adrian Chastain -- t15. From Puritan to Quaker: Mary Dyer and Puritan-Quaker Conversion in the Seventeenth-Century Atlantic / rMonroy, Rachel Love -- tVI. Imperial Worlds -- t16. Pennsylvania's Religious Freedom in Comparative Colonial Context / rHaefeli, Evan -- t17. William Penn and Security Communities: A Career / rCecil, Patrick -- t18. William Penn's Imperial Landscape: Improvement, Political Economy, and Colonial Agriculture in the Pennsylvania Project / rWanibuchi, Shuichi -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWilliam Penn was an instrumental and controversial figure in the early modern transatlantic world, known both as a leader in the movement for religious toleration in England and as a founder of two American colonies, Pennsylvania and New Jersey. As such, his career was marked by controversy and contention in both England and America. This volume looks at William Penn with fresh eyes, bringing together scholars from a range of disciplines to assess his multifaceted life and career. Contributors analyze the worlds that shaped Penn and the worlds that he shaped: Irish, English, American, Quaker, and imperial. The eighteen chapters in The Worlds of William Penn shed critical new light on Penn's life and legacy, examining his early and often-overlooked time in Ireland; the literary, political, and theological legacies of his public career during the Restoration and after the 1688 Revolution; his role as proprietor of Pennsylvania; his religious leadership in the Quaker movement, and as a loyal lieutenant to George Fox, and his important role in the broader British imperial project. Coinciding with the 300th anniversary of Penn's death the time is right for this examination of Penn's importance both in his own time and to the ongoing campaign for political and religious liberty  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aCecil, Patrick.1 aErben, Patrick M.1 aGallo, Marcus.1 aGill, Catie.1 aGoode, Michael.1 aHaefeli, Evan.1 aHorning, Audrey.1 aMann, Emily.1 aMazzaferro, Alexander.1 aMilroy, Elizabeth.1 aMonroy, Rachel Love.1 aMurphy, Andrew R.1 aMurphy, Andrew R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aRoeber, Catharine Dann.1 aSauer, Elizabeth.1 aSmith, Sarah A. Morgan.1 aSmolenski, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aSowerby, Scott.1 aWanibuchi, Shuichi.1 aWeimer, Adrian Chastain.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2019z978311065352640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978801806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978801806.jpg  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065352-6  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DEGb2019  aZDB-23-DGGb2019